    "last_activity_date" : 1563285367,
    "creation_date" : 1563285367,
    "answer_id" : 57058973,
    "question_id" : 2369967,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Method to check array for null or empty also is present on org.apache.commons.lang:</p>\n\n<pre><code>import org.apache.commons.lang.ArrayUtils;\n\nArrayUtils.isEmpty(array);\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 4280750,
      "reputation" : 1933,
      "user_id" : 3500196,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/2DzO5.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Shivang Agarwal",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3500196/shivang-agarwal"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 4,
    "last_activity_date" : 1587503890,
    "creation_date" : 1587503890,
    "answer_id" : 61353427,
    "question_id" : 2369967,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>In Java 8+ you achieve this with the help of streams allMatch method.</p>\n\n<p>For primitive:</p>\n\n<pre><code>int[] k = new int[3];\nArrays.stream(k).allMatch(element -&gt; element != 0)\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>For Object:</p>\n\n<pre><code>Objects[] k = new Objects[3];\nArrays.stream(k).allMatch(Objects::nonNull)\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
